ons alive in their New World enclaves. Although elevators have replaced walkups and fancy Italian restaurants and upscale boutiques have replaced mom-and-pop storefronts, the "old neighborhood" and its Italian village roots survive in these photographs of la vita di "idianità.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantszMassachusettszBostonvBiographyvPictorial works. 0aItalian AmericanszMassachusettszBostonvBiographyvPictorial works. 0aItalian AmericanszMassachusettszBostonxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aLittle ItalieszMassachusettszBostonxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Italian American Studies. 4aArea Studies : Italian Studies. 4aPublic Policy : Immigration. 7aPhotography / Photoessays & Documentaries.2bisacsh1 aPasto, James S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846701640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438467016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438467016/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles